      <h2>Battery</h2>

      <div class="note">
        The battery pack is not fully charged out of the carton. Charge it fully before first use. Charge only in a DeWALT charger, at an air temperature between 40&deg;F (4.5&deg;C) and 104&deg;F (40&deg;C). Best life and performance comes from charging at 65&ndash;75&deg;F (18&ndash;24&deg;C).
      </div>

      <h3>Installing and Removing the Battery Pack (Fig. E)</h3>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcn623/figE.jpg" alt="Battery pack aligning with the rails inside the pin nailer handle, with the release button callout for removal" />
        <figcaption>Fig. E &mdash; align the pack with the rails in the handle and slide it in until firmly seated</figcaption>
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li><strong>Install:</strong> ensure the tool is off, align the battery pack <strong>(1)</strong> with the rails inside the handle, and slide it in until it is firmly seated and will not disengage.</li>
        <li><strong>Remove:</strong> press the release button <strong>(2)</strong> and firmly pull the pack out of the handle.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Preparing the Tool</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Read the nailer safety warnings.</li>
        <li>Put on eye and ear protection.</li>
        <li>Remove the battery from the tool.</li>
        <li>Make sure the magazine is empty of all fasteners.</li>
        <li>Check the pusher assembly for smooth, proper movement. Do not use the tool if it is not functioning properly.</li>
        <li>Keep the tool pointed away from yourself and others.</li>
        <li>Insert a fully charged battery pack.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Proper Hand Position (Fig. D)</h3>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcn623/figD.jpg" alt="Correct grip on the pin nailer with one hand wrapped around the handle" />
        <figcaption>Fig. D &mdash; one hand on the handle (3); always hold securely in anticipation of recoil</figcaption>
      </div>

      <h2>Loading the Tool (Fig. F)</h2>

      <div class="note">
        Use only pins recommended for your nailer that meet DeWALT specifications &mdash; see the Specifications table.
      </div>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcn623/figF.jpg" alt="Loading a stick of 23 gauge pins into the open magazine of the pin nailer, with magazine release lever and magazine callouts" />
        <figcaption>Fig. F &mdash; loading the magazine</figcaption>
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Depress the magazine release lever <strong>(6)</strong>.</li>
        <li>Pull the sliding portion of the magazine <strong>(7)</strong> back.</li>
        <li>Load the stick of pins with the arrow pattern pointing to the left as shown. If the pins have black dots instead of arrows, position the dots up.</li>
        <li>Close the magazine until it latches. The tool is now ready for use.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Operation</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Turn the unit off and remove the battery pack before making any adjustments or installing/removing accessories. An accidental start-up can cause injury.
      </div>

      <h3>Dry-Fire Lockout (Fig. A)</h3>
      <p>The tool detects when about 10 pins remain and shuts off. The dry-fire light <strong>(13)</strong> glows red when the trigger is actuated. Load more pins and the light turns off and the tool returns to normal function.</p>

      <h3>Two-Trigger Actuation</h3>
      <p>The primary trigger <strong>(4)</strong> can fire the tool only after the secondary trigger <strong>(5)</strong>, located under the primary trigger, has been pulled. To fire: first grasp the secondary trigger under the hand grip, then pull the primary trigger.</p>

      <div class="warning">
        While the secondary trigger remains squeezed, the tool fires each time the primary trigger is pulled. Never hold the secondary trigger except during fastening, and never inadvertently grasp it when moving, holstering, or preparing the work surface.
      </div>

      <h3>Tool Operation Check (Fig. A)</h3>
      <div class="warning">Remove all fasteners from the tool before performing this check.</div>
      <ol>
        <li>Place the nose against a workpiece for all checks.</li>
        <li>With your hand at the rear of the handle and <em>not</em> squeezing the secondary trigger, pull the primary trigger. <strong>The tool must NOT cycle.</strong></li>
        <li>With the secondary trigger squeezed, pull the primary trigger. <strong>The tool MUST cycle.</strong></li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Cold and Hot Weather</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Below freezing:</strong> keep the tool as warm as possible before use and actuate it 5 or 6 times into scrap timber before working.</li>
        <li><strong>Hot weather:</strong> the tool operates normally, but keep it out of direct sunlight &mdash; excessive heat degrades bumpers and rubber parts.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Adjusting Drive Depth</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        To reduce the risk of accidental actuation while adjusting depth: remove the battery pack, engage the trigger lock-off, point the nose away from you, and avoid contact with the trigger.
      </div>

      <p>The depth of drive is factory set to a nominal value. Test fire a pin and check the depth. Using the depth adjustment wheel <strong>(10)</strong>:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>To drive the pin <strong>deeper</strong>, rotate the wheel to the right.</li>
        <li>To drive the pin <strong>shallower</strong>, rotate the wheel to the left.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>Test drive another pin and repeat as needed.</p>

      <h2>Clearing a Jam (Fig. A, G)</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Always turn the unit off and remove the battery pack before clearing a jammed pin.
      </div>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcn623/figG.jpg" alt="Tool-free jam release with the nose cover lifted, showing the inner nose cover (15) sliding forward and the pinch lever (16) that locks the mechanism" />
        <figcaption>Fig. G &mdash; tool-free jam release: lift the nose cover, slide the inner nose cover (15) forward, then press the pinch lever (16) down to relock</figcaption>
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Remove the battery pack from the tool.</li>
        <li>Depress the magazine release lever <strong>(6)</strong> and pull the magazine <strong>(7)</strong> back to stop pin feeding.</li>
        <li>Remove the no-mar tip <strong>(9)</strong>.</li>
        <li>Grab the small tabs on each side of the nose cover <strong>(8)</strong> and pull up.</li>
        <li>With the nose cover lifted, slide the inner nose cover <strong>(15)</strong> forward and lift up to clear the jammed pin.</li>
        <li>Push the pinch lever <strong>(16)</strong> down to lock the mechanism back to operating position.</li>
        <li>Reattach the no-mar tip.</li>
        <li>Close the magazine and reconnect the battery pack.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Belt Hook (Fig. A)</h2>
      <p>The integrated belt hook <strong>(11)</strong> mounts on either side of the tool for left- or right-handed users, or can be removed entirely.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove the battery pack from the tool.</li>
        <li>To switch sides, remove the screw <strong>(12)</strong> from the opposite side and reattach the belt hook <strong>(11)</strong> on the other side.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Maintenance</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Turn the unit off and remove the battery pack before any maintenance. An accidental start-up can cause injury.
      </div>

      <h3>Cleaning the Driver Path (Fig. A, G)</h3>
      <p>Glue from the pin strip may build up in the driver path and prevent the tool from driving pins properly.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove the battery pack <strong>(1)</strong>.</li>
        <li>Remove the pin strip from the tool.</li>
        <li>Open the tool-free jam release (see Clearing a Jam).</li>
        <li>Apply a small amount of tool oil to a clean cloth and wipe the pin channel until any glue is removed.</li>
        <li>Reinstall the drive cover.</li>
        <li>Insert a pin strip and reinstall the battery.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>General Cleaning</h3>
      <div class="warning">
        Blow dirt and dust out of all air vents with clean, dry air at least once a week. Wear ANSI Z87.1 eye protection when doing this.
      </div>
      <p>Never use solvents or harsh chemicals on the non-metallic parts &mdash; they weaken the plastic. Use a cloth dampened only with water and mild soap. Never let liquid get inside the tool or immerse any part of it.</p>

      <h2>Troubleshooting</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        To reduce the risk of serious injury, always disconnect the battery pack from the tool before any repair.
      </div>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Symptom</th><th>Cause</th><th>Fix</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Headlights don't come on when secondary trigger is depressed</td><td>Dry-fire lockout engaged (red light on)</td><td>Load pins into the magazine.</td></tr>
          <tr><td></td><td>Low or damaged battery; pack not fully inserted</td><td>Check charge, charge or replace the pack, and confirm it is fully seated.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Red dry-fire lockout light comes on</td><td>Low pin count</td><td>Load pins into the magazine.</td></tr>
          <tr><td></td><td>Pin jammed in magazine or nose</td><td>Clean the magazine/nose; watch for broken pin fragments in the channel.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Tool does not actuate with both triggers depressed</td><td>Dry-fire lockout engaged</td><td>Load pins into the magazine.</td></tr>
          <tr><td></td><td>Tool timed out (triggers held 10&ndash;20 seconds)</td><td>Release both triggers for an automatic electronic reset.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Headlights flash after both triggers are depressed</td><td>Low battery charge</td><td>Check charge level and charge if necessary.</td></tr>
          <tr><td></td><td>Electronics need a reset</td><td>Remove the battery, wait 3 seconds, and reinsert.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Tool operates but does not drive pins fully</td><td>Depth set too shallow</td><td>Rotate the depth adjust to a deeper setting.</td></tr>
          <tr><td></td><td>Tool not firmly applied to the workpiece</td><td>Apply adequate force to hold the tool tight against the workpiece.</td></tr>
          <tr><td></td><td>Wrong pin type/length for the material; pins inserted backwards</td><td>Confirm pin type, size, and orientation match the application.</td></tr>
          <tr><td></td><td>Damaged driver blade</td><td>Order and install a replacement driver blade assembly.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Tool operates but no pin is driven</td><td>Wrong size/type fastener, or pins of unequal length / loaded tips forward</td><td>See pin specifications; load equal-length pins with tips at the front of the magazine.</td></tr>
          <tr><td></td><td>Debris or jammed pin in nose/magazine</td><td>Clean the magazine and nose area.</td></tr>
          <tr><td></td><td>Tool too cold</td><td>Cycle the tool against scrap until it begins firing pins.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Driver blade stuck in down position</td><td>Dirty drive path or jammed pin</td><td>Clean the nose driver path and underside of the door; remove jam.</td></tr>
          <tr><td></td><td>Damaged blade, worn seals, or lack of lubrication</td><td>See an authorized service center.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>For more serious or persistent problems, contact a DeWALT service center or call 1&#8209;800&#8209;4&#8209;DeWALT.</p>

